			<ns0:name>dsprin...@google.com</ns0:name><ns0:uri>/u/112723007196297768207/</ns0:uri></ns0:author><ns0:content type="html">void* kBadAddr = reinterpret_cast&amp;lt;void*&amp;gt;(~0U);

void* brk_addr = sysbrk(kBadAddr);

will set errno to EINVAL (not sure what it's supposed to be; the old sbrk API generally use ENOMEM), and sets |brk_addr| to whatever the old break address was (equivalent of calling sysbrk(NULL)).  I expected |brk_addr| to get set to (void*)(-1) (see, e.g. http://nativeclient.googlecode.com/svn/data/docs_tarball/nacl/googleclient/native_client/scons-out/doc/html/group__syscalls.html#gfdb60e6e9d2dd663e3cc8a13ef796877)

I was not able to find an official spec on sysbrk(), so I'm not really sure what the right thing is.</ns0:content><ns0:updated>2011-11-08T19:16:16.000Z</ns0:updated><ns0:published>2010-08-20T22:49:16.000Z</ns0:published><ns2:status>Fixed</ns2:status><ns2:owner>
